			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Summoner's Boon 
<br />
Classes: 
<br />
None  
<br />
Description: 
<br />
1: Pet Power Increase(15)
<br />
2: Limit: Max Level(70)
<br />
3: Limit: Min Level(59) 
<br />

<br />
As observed by a bst w/this focus on his pet:
<br />
"Has raised Max Hit from 77 - 79 
<br />
Over all gave a 3.2% DPS Boost "
<br />

<br />
Another observation:
<br />

<br />
"UnAug'd Pet's Stats: 32.43 DPS, 57.73% to Hit, 4000 HP, 2 - 3% Life Regen (80 - 120 HP Regen), Hits for 78 Max 
<br />

<br />
Aug'd Pet's Stats: 33.96 DPS, 60.98% to Hit, 4800 HP, 5 - 6% Life Regen (240 - 288 HP Regen), Hits for 80 Max 
<br />

<br />
POSITIVE DIFFERENCES: 1.53 DPS, 3.25% to Hit, 800 HP more, 160 - 168 HP Regen, 2 Damage Max, Pet is Bigger as well."
<br />

<br />
So for easy math, say it is a 3% dps boost plus regen and hp buff...on the current dmg table instead of hitting for 100dps it will now hit for 103 dps...hrmm
<br />

<br />
So on charm brk if it hits for 500 dps(since 100 is 20% of 500 according to the dmg table for what a charm pet should do)  then the mob will then hit for 515dps and have regen plus a hp bonus.  Well thats nice.
<br />

<br />
Maybe if we had adc on the top ten with this focus that would be cool.  But how many chanters currently buff their charmed pets now.  Isn't it more common practice to play root reverse charm in the new zones?</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
